I attached the file issueresolved.vm, where I made the changes to view the custom field (Freetext with wiki renderer) 10150:

{code}
  #if($issue.getCustomFieldValue("customfield_10150"))
    <tr bgcolor="#ffffff"><td>
        <b>Analyse:</b> <br/>
	<pre>
        $issue.getCustomFieldValue("customfield_10150")
	</pre>
    </td></tr>
  #end
{code}

The custom field contains e.g. the following entry in wiki notation:
{code}
Line 1: *bold text*

Line 3: {{monospaced text}}
{code}

The way it is implemented right now renders the following output:
{panel}
Line 1: \*bold text\* Line 3: \{ \{monospaced text\}\}
{panel}

However, I want the output to be rendered ideally with the renderer configured for this field. If that does not work, I would also hardcode the wiki renderer. (As for my understanding, the wiki-text must somehow be translated to HTML, so that it is correctly inserted into the HTML eMail.

Reference: http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Adding+Custom+Fields+to+Email

I just received this email from an user that repeatedly complains that JIRA kicks him out after period of inactivity, even if he checks the 'remember me' box on the login screen:

{quote}
Figured it out... really brain dead on my part.
On another PC I set the remember me checkbox, so only after logging out on that machine did it allow the other machine to keep logged in.
{quote}

I've had multiple reports of JIRA not remembering logon, but so far this comes closest to reproducible scenario.

Currently we get a not-insignificant number of performance related cases to JIRA, these require comparatively very large investments of time and debugging as against our other customers.

JIRA and the java JVM under the right conditions have a tendency to just 'trod along' when resources are tight, and I recently came across a case in [JSP-32621|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/JSP-32621] whereby a number of relatively inexpensive, concurrent issue-subscriptions turned into a long-running task which ate gargantuan amounts of memory.
{code:title=SubscriptionMailQueue.java}                List groupUser = group.getUsers();
                for (int i = 0; i < groupUser.size(); i++)
                {
                    String userName = (String) groupUser.get(i);
                    User user;
                    try
                    {
                        user = UserManager.getInstance().getUser(userName);
                        sendSearchRequestEmail(user);
                    }
                    catch (EntityNotFoundException enfe)
                    {
                        log.warn("User '" + userName + "' referenced in subscription '" + subscription.getLong("id") + "' of filter '" + subscription.getLong("filterID") + "' does not exist.");
                    }
                }
{code}

The code above in the send() iterates through each User on the subscription recipient list and tries to get the cached Searcher from the searchRequest, but, under periods of very high garbage collection, at the end of each iteration the Searcher will be temporarily dereferenced off the stack; and at this point the GC clears out the former Search result and when the for loop resumes it must again perform the expensive Lucene query and sort, prior to sending off the subscription.

I am not fully aware of the impact but would it be worth it to hold a reference to the cached subscription result prior to the recipient iteration so that the Searcher cannot be cleared by the GC? The problem is this issue begets itself, if JIRA gets into some period of sparse memory, and a subscription is fired, this can have a tangible, long-lasting and often fatal effect.

Potentially I think this issue might come into play with a significant number of customers, those with large installs, with many filters, subscriptions and users.

Thanks
Peter

When JIRA is installed as a service from the command line in service.bat (service.bat install JIRA) the {{-Dorg.apache.jasper.runtime.BodyContentImpl.LIMIT_BUFFER=true}} parameter is invoked to stop a memory leak in Tomcat [caching|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Causes+of+OutOfMemoryErrors#CausesofOutOfMemoryErrors-Tomcatmemoryleak] JSPs.

The line is executed as 

{quote}"%EXECUTABLE%" //US//%SERVICE_NAME% ++JvmOptions "-Dorg.apache.jasper.runtime.BodyContentImpl.LIMIT_BUFFER=true -Djava.io.tmpdir=%CATALINA_BASE%\temp;-Djava.util.logging.manager=org.apache.juli.ClassLoaderLogManager;-Djava.util.logging.config.file=%CATALINA_BASE%\conf\logging.properties" --JvmMs 128 --JvmMx 512 --Startup auto || call "%~dp0\permgenservice.bat"{quote}

when there should be a ; delimiter between {{-Dorg.apache.jasper.runtime.BodyContentImpl.LIMIT_BUFFER=true -Djava.io.tmpdir=%CATALINA_BASE%\temp;}}

It should be

{quote}"%EXECUTABLE%" //US//%SERVICE_NAME% ++JvmOptions "-Dorg.apache.jasper.runtime.BodyContentImpl.LIMIT_BUFFER=true;-Djava.io.tmpdir=%CATALINA_BASE%\temp;
-Djava.util.logging.manager=org.apache.juli.ClassLoaderLogManager;-Djava.util.logging.config.file=%CATALINA_BASE%\conf\logging.properties" --JvmMs 128 --JvmMx 512 --Startup auto || call "%~dp0\permgenservice.bat"{quote}

The workaround for existing installs is to modify the entry directly in the windows registry.

